{
  "answer": "**Viṣṇu Smṛti (Chapter 35)** explicitly lists the *mahāpātakas* (great sins) as: (1) killing a Brāhmaṇa, (2) drinking liquor, (3) stealing a Brāhmaṇa's gold, and (4) violating a preceptor's bed; (5) association with such a person is also included.[^1]\n\n**Manusmṛti (Chapter 11, verse 54)** lists them identically as: (1) the slaying of a Brahmana, (2) the drinking of liquor, (3) theft (of gold, per context in 11.57), (4) the defiling of a guru's bed; these are called great sins (*mahāpātakas*), along with (5) association with them.[^2]\n\nThe lists name the **same five sins, in the **same order**. Neither text drops, adds, nor rearranges any; the phrasing is nearly identical (e.g., *guru*'s bed vs. *preceptor*'s bed; generic \"theft\" vs. specified \"Brāhmaṇa's gold,\" but both refer to gold theft as the third). \n\n[^1]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 35, [paragraph](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/35/translation/#p-6491a0).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 12 (containing verses from Chapter 11), [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-961cc5). The corpus labels this as Chapter 12 but includes Mn_11 content. Context for \"theft\" as gold: [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-fb70bb).",
